  "final_answer": "The relatively low-priced coastal areas are concentrated in a handful of coastal tracts that are far below the overall coastal median house value of 219,450.\n\nLowest-priced examples\n- NEAR OCEAN at (-120.59, 34.70): 28,300\n- NEAR BAY at (-122.41, 37.78): 32,500\n- NEAR OCEAN at (-119.85, 34.40): 37,500\n- NEAR BAY at (-122.37, 37.93): 37,900\n- NEAR OCEAN at (-120.69, 35.34): 42,500\n- <1H OCEAN at (-116.99, 33.46): 43,000\n- <1H OCEAN at (-122.01, 37.40): 47,500\n- <1H OCEAN at (-123.72, 41.09): 50,000\n- NEAR OCEAN at (-124.23, 40.81): 50,800\n- NEAR OCEAN at (-119.09, 34.22): 52,500\n\nWhat likely explains the lower prices\n- Lower incomes: Many of these tracts have median incomes well below the coastal median income of 3.79, suggesting weaker local purchasing power.\n- More crowding: Several areas have high population per household, which can point to overcrowding or less desirable housing conditions.\n- Smaller or denser units: Higher bedrooms_per_room often suggests smaller or more cramped homes, which can reduce value.\n- Housing stock differences: Some of the lower-priced places appear to have relatively newer housing, which in this context may reflect more modest or lower-cost development rather than premium coastal housing.\n- Location alone is not enough: Being near the ocean helps, but local neighborhood conditions and housing quality still strongly affect prices.\n\nImportant caveat\n- These are single-record locations, so they should be interpreted cautiously as signals of low-priced coastal pockets rather than broad regional conclusions.",
